<chapter xml:id="AI">
    <title>Academic Integrity and Course Standards</title>
    
    <p>The goals of academic integrity are (i) to give credit where credit is due, and (ii) to create a record that enables other learners and scholars to trace the development of ideas. Ultimately, the work that you submit should honestly reflect your own personal understanding and effort and no one else’s.</p>
    
    <p>A good rule of thumb is to always cite your sources, resources, or people that you received assistance from, with as much specificity as possible. Please ask me if you have any questions about balancing academic integrity and group work. Collaboration can be a valuable tool, especially for assignments where the intention is for you to practice and learn! However, please jot a note in the margins of your written solutions for any steps that you received assistance with to practice integrity.</p>

    <section xml:id="section-expectations">
        <title>Expectations for Assessment</title>
        <p>To ensure fair assessment for everyone, the following expectations apply to all course materials:</p>
        
        <ul>
            <li>
                <title>Authorized vs. Unauthorized Aids</title>
                <p>You are expected to present work that is your own. Using unauthorized tools (including, but not limited to, AI, unauthorized calculators, hidden notes, or soliciting external assistance) on any assignment or exam is a violation of academic integrity.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Verification of Authenticity</title>
                <p>You are strongly encouraged to maintain handwritten notes and preliminary computations. In the event of a suspected violation, you may be asked to explain your work or demonstrate your understanding of the concepts involved.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Retroactive Review Policy</title>
                <p>When a student is found to be engaging in academic dishonesty on any assignment or assessment, it calls into question the authenticity of all previous work. To ensure the fairness and validity of the final grade, the instructor reserves the right to review all previously submitted coursework. If evidence of unauthorized assistance is identified in earlier assessments, grades may be retroactively adjusted to reflect a lack of demonstrated mastery.</p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <p><em>Any infractions will be dealt with according to the Discipline and Penalties listed in the student handbook, including potential scholastic penalties and a report filed with Student Services.</em></p>
</chapter>